idents of the United States]]\n[[Category:Second Party System]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Democrats]]\n[[Category:Tennessee lawyers]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Jacksonians]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1844 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:1840 United States vice-presidential candidates]]\n[[Category:University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill alumni]]\n", "name_user": "173.216.2.80", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_K._Polk"}
{"title_page": "Under the Skin (2013 film)", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Under the Skin (1997 film)}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Under the Skin\n| image = Under the Skin poster.png\n| alt =\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Jonathan Glazer]]\n| producer       = {{plainlist|\n* James Wilson\n* [[Nick Wechsler (producer)|Nick Wechsler]]\n|}}\n| screenplay     = {{plainlist|\n* Walter Campbell\n* Jonathan Glazer\n|}}\n| based on       = {{based on|''[[Under the Skin (novel)|Under the Skin]]''|[[Michel Faber]]}}\n| starring       = [[Scarlett Johansson]]\n| music          = [[Micachu|Mica Levi]]\n| cinematography = [[Daniel Landin]]\n| editing        = Paul Watts\n| studio         = {{plainlist|\n* [[British Film Institute|BFI]]\n* [[Film4]]\n}}\n| distributor    = {{plainlist|\n* [[StudioCanal]] {{small|(UK)}}\n* [[A24 (company)|A24]] {{small|(US)}}\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2013|08|29|[[Telluride Film Festival|Telluride]]|2014|03|14|UK|2014|04|04|US}}\n| runtime        = 108 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 107:59--><ref>{{cite web|title=''UNDER THE SKIN'' (15)|url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/under-skin-film|work=[[British Board of Film Classification]]|date=3 January 2014|accessdate=11 April 2014}}</ref>\n| country        = {{plainlist|\n* United Kingdom<ref name=bfi>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b8b0e572a|title=Under the Skin (2014)|work=[[British Film Institute]]|accessdate=21 August 2017}}</ref>\n* United States<ref name=bfi/>\n* Switzerland<ref name=bfi/>\n|}}\n| language       = English\n| budget         = [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]8 million<br />([[United States dollar|$]]13.3 million)<ref name=\"SD\" >{{cite web|last=Wiseman |first=Andreas |url=http://www.screendaily.com/features/under-the-skin-at-any-cost/5069904.article |title=Under The Skin: at any cost &#124; Features &#124; Screen |work=[[Screen Daily]] |date=24 March 2014 |accessdate=14 April 2014}}</ref>\n| gross          = \u00a35.2 million <br />($7.2 million)<ref name=\"TN\" >{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Under-the-Skin#tab=summary |title=''Under the Skin'' (2014)|work=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|publisher=Nash Information Services, LLC|accessdate=13 November 2016}}</ref>\n}}'''''Under the Skin''''' is a 2013 <!-- Per Wikipedia's film guidelines, do not say British-American, unless so deemed. --> [[science fiction film]] <!-- Please don't add additional genres - we should only have the main genre, as per [[WP:FILMLEAD]] -->directed by [[Jonathan Glazer]] with a screenplay by Glazer and Walter Campbell. The film is loosely based on the [[Under the Skin (novel)|2000 novel]] by [[Michel Faber]]. It stars [[Scarlett Johansson]] as an otherworldly woman who preys on men in [[Scotland]]. The film premiered at [[Telluride Film Festival]] on 29 August 2013. It was released in the UK on 14 March 2014 and the United States on 4 April 2014.\n\nGlazer developed ''Under the Skin'' for over a decade; he and co-screenwriter Walter Campbell pared it back from an elaborate, special effects-heavy concept to a sparse story focusing on an alien perspective of the human world. Most characters were played by non-actors, and many scenes were filmed with [[hidden camera]]s.\n\nWith a total worldwide gross of \u00a35.2 million,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=undertheskin2014.htm|title=Under the Skin (2014) (2014) - Box Office Mojo|website=www.boxofficemojo.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-29}}</ref> ''Under the Skin'' was a [[Box office bomb|box office failure]]. Nevertheless, it received critical acclaim, particularly for Johansson's performance, Glazer's direction, and [[Micachu|Mica Levi]]'s score. It received [[List of accolades received by Under the Skin (2013 film)|multiple awards]] and was named one of the best films of the year and the decade by several publications. It ranks 61st on the [[BBC's 100 Greatest Films of the 21st Century]] list.\n\n== Plot ==<!-- Per WP:FILMPLOT, film summaries must be between 400 and 700  words. Please don't add unnecessary detail. -->\nIn [[Glasgow]], a motorcyclist ([[Jeremy McWilliams]]) retrieves an inert young woman (Lynsey Taylor Mackay) from the roadside and places her in the back of a van, where a naked woman ([[Scarlett Johansson]]) dons her clothes. After buying clothes and make-up at a shopping centre, the woman drives the van around Scotland, picking up men. She lures a man (Joe Szula) into a dilapidated house. As he undresses, following the woman into a void, he is submerged in a liquid abyss.\n\nAt a beach, the woman attempts to pick up a swimmer ([[Kry\u0161tof H\u00e1dek]]), but is interrupted by the cries of a drowning couple. The swimmer rescues the husband, but the husband rushes back into the water to save his wife and both drown. As the swimmer lies exhausted on the beach, the woman strikes his head with a rock, drags him to the van, and drives away, ignoring the couple's distraught baby. Later that night, the motorcyclist retrieves the swimmer's belongings, ignoring the baby, who is still on the beach.\n\nThe woman visits a nightclub and picks up another man ([[Paul Brannigan]]). At the house, he follows her into the void and is submerged in the liquid. Suspended beneath the surface, he sees the swimmer floating naked beside him, alive but bloated and almost immobile. When he reaches to touch him, the swimmer's body collapses and a red mass empties through a trough.\n\nThe next day, the woman receives a rose from a street vendor, purchased from another man in traffic. She then listens to a radio report about the missing family from the beach. The woman then seduces a lonely man with facial disfigurement ([[Adam Pearson (actor)|Adam Pearson]]) but lets him leave after examining herself in a mirror. The motorcyclist intercepts the man and bundles him into a car, then sets out in pursuit of the woman with three other motorcyclists.\n\nIn the [[Scottish Highlands]], the woman abandons the van in the fog. She walks to a restaurant and attempts to eat cake, but retches and spits it out. At a bus stop, she meets a man (Michael Moreland) who offers to help her. At his house, he prepares a meal for her and they watch television. Alone in her room, she examines her body in a mirror. They visit a ruined castle, where the man carries her over a puddle and helps her down some steps. At his house, they kiss and begin to have sex, but the woman stops and examines her genitals.\n\nWandering in a forest, the woman meets a commercial logger (Dave Acton) and shelters in a [[bothy]]. She awakes to find the logger molesting her. She runs into the wilderness but he catches and attempts to rape her; he tears her skin, revealing a black, featureless body. As the woman extricates herself from her skin, the man douses her in fuel and burns her alive. Elsewhere, the motorcyclist stands on a mountaintop and looks out across a snowy field.\n\n== Production ==\n=== Pre-production ===\nDirector [[Jonathan Glazer]] decided to adapt [[Michel Faber]]'s novel ''[[Under the Skin (novel)|Under the Skin]]'' (2000) after finishing his debut film ''[[Sexy Beast]]'' (2000), but work did not begin until he had finished his second film, ''[[Birth (film)|Birth]]'' (2004).<ref name=\":11\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/mar/06/under-the-skin-director-jonathan-glazer-scarlett-johansson|title=Under the Skin: why did this chilling masterpiece take a decade? |last=Leigh |first=Danny | date=2014-03-06 | website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-01-29}}</ref> Glazer's producer James Wilson sent him a script that closely adapted the novel; Glazer admired the script but had no interest in filming it, saying: \"I knew then that I absolutely didn't want to film the book. But I still wanted to make the book a film.\"<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nGlazer and co-writer Milo Addica, later replaced by Walter Campbell, spent several years writing and rewriting the story. They conceived an elaborate high-budget film, and produced a script about two aliens disguised as husband-and-wife farmers. [[Brad Pitt]] was cast as the husband, but progress was slow.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/mar/06/under-the-skin-director-jonathan-glazer-scarlett-johansson|title=Under the Skin: why did this chilling masterpiece take a decade?|last1=Leigh|first1=Danna|date=6 March 2014|website=The Guardian|accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref> Glazer eventually decided to make a film that represented an alien perspective of the human world and focused only on the female character.<ref name=\":7\" /> He and Campbell deleted every scene in their script that did not involve her and deleted the elaborate special effects sequences, a process Glazer likened to \"a big, extravagant rock band turning into [[PJ Harvey]]\".<ref name=\":7\" /> The film also removes the character names.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/artsandculture/article/19230/1/how-to-write-a-minimal-masterpiece-script|title=How to write a minimal masterpiece script|first=|last=Dazed|date=12 March 2014|publisher=|accessdate=8 May 2018}}</ref> Whereas the novel is explicit that the main character is an alien processing humans for meat, the film is more ambiguous.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite news|url=https://uproxx.com/hitfix/did-scarlett-johansson-really-walk-around-scotland-unnoticed-filming-under-the-skin/|title=Did Scarlett Johansson really walk around Scotland unnoticed filming \u2018Under the Skin?\u2019|date=2014-04-07|work=UPROXX|access-date=2018-07-21|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nGlazer shot commercials while the film was in pre-production, which he used to \"sketch\" ideas and test equipment.<ref name=\":8\">{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2014/10/why-jonathan-glazers-under-the-skin-took-a-decade-to-make-videos-190464/|title=Why Jonathan Glazer\u2019s \u2018Under the Skin\u2019 Took a Decade to Make (VIDEOS)|last1=Thompson|first1=Anne|date=23 October 2014|website=IndieWire|accessdate=3 November 2016}}</ref> ''Under the Skin'' was jointly financed by [[Film4 Productions]], the [[British Film Institute]], [[Scottish Screen]], Silver Reel, and [[FilmNation Entertainment]]. Glazer secured final backing after cutting the elaborate special effects scenes from the script.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n=== Casting ===\n[[Gemma Arterton]],<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/gemma-arterton-on-the-voices-and-why-shes-turned-her-back-on-hollywood-10114571.html|title=Gemma Arterton on black comedy The Voices and why she's turned her back on Hollywood|last=Aftab|first=Kaleem|date=17 March 2015|accessdate=1 April 2015|location=London|website=The Independent}}</ref> [[Eva Green]], [[January Jones]], [[Abbie Cornish]] and [[Olivia Wilde]] were considered for the lead.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/film/jonathan-glazer-the-joy-of-division-1.1715260?page=1|title=Jonathan Glazer: the joy of division|newspaper=The Irish Times|access-date=2016-11-03|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2015, Arterton stated that she had been Glazer's first choice but the film had needed a bigger star to get funding.<ref name=\":10\" /> The role went to [[Scarlett Johansson]], who remained committed to the project for four years before it reached completion.<ref name=\":8\" /> Johansson was well known for her roles in [[Blockbuster (entertainment)|blockbuster]] films such as the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] franchise. Glazer said: \"It made a great deal of sense to cast somebody very well known out of context. I remember seeing her walking along the street in a pink jumper on a long lens and she looks like an exotic insect on the wrong continent.\"<ref name=\":9\" /> Despite her fame, Johansson was rarely recognised, as members of the public did not believe it could be her.<ref name=\":9\" /> For the role she learnt to drive a van and master an English accent.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nChampionship motorcycle [[Road racing|road racer]] [[Jeremy McWilliams]] was cast as the motorcyclist, as the film required a \"world-class\" motorcyclist who could ride through the Scottish Highlands at high speeds in bad weather. The logger was played by the owner of a location researched for the film.<ref name=\"film4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.film4.com/special-features/interviews/under-the-skin-casting|title=Under The Skin: Casting|website=Film 4|accessdate=28 June 2014}}</ref> For the man with disfigurement, Glazer did not want to use [[Craniofacial prosthesis|prosthetics]]. To cast the role, the production team contacted the charity [[Changing Faces (charity)|Changing Faces]], which supports people with facial disfigurements. The role went to [[Adam Pearson (actor)|Adam Pearson]], who has [[neurofibromatosis]] and had worked in television productions. Pearson's suggestions about how Johansson's character could lure his character were used in the script.<ref name=\"film4\" />\n\n=== Filming ===\n[[File:Tantallon_castle_1.jpg|thumb|242x242px|Parts of ''Under the Skin'' were shot at [[Tantallon Castle]] in [[East Lothian]], Scotland.<ref>(2015) '''Filmed here - 2012, Under The Skin, Jonathan Glazer''' Film Edinburgh, Retrieved 20 February 2015</ref>]]As Glazer wanted the film to feel realistic,<ref name=\":7\" /> most characters were played by non-actors. Many scenes, such as those set in the nightclub and shopping centre, and the scenes in which Johansson's character picks up men in the van, were unscripted sequences filmed with [[hidden camera]]s.<ref name=\":12\"/><ref name=\":13\" /> The production team would inform the subjects they had been filmed and ask permission to use the footage.<ref name=\":12\" /> Glazer said the men were \"talked through what extremes they would have to go to if they agreed to take part in the film once they understood what we were doing\".<ref name=\":13\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-26559813|title=Scarlett Johansson on playing 'unscripted' scavenging alien|last1=Jones|first1=Emma|date=16 March 2014|accessdate=17 March 2014|publisher=BBC|website=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nThe crew built their own cameras to shoot some scenes.<ref name=\":8\" /> Johansson drove the van with the crew inside, and towed a trailer containing a generator for their equipment.<ref name=\":12\"/> To create the black room in which the character traps men, the crew built a bespoke set with a reflective floor, blackout, and custom lighting. The actors were filmed walking into a pool whose floor sank as they walked, submerging them. The scenes were finished with [[computer graphics]].<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n\n{{album ratings\n\n|rev1=[[Allmusic]]\n\n|rev1score={{rating|5|5}}<ref>[https://www.allmusic.com/album/under-the-skin-original-motion-picture-soundtrack-mw0002618596 Allmusic]</ref>\n\n|rev2=[[Pitchfork (magazine)|Pitchfork]]\n\n|rev2score=7.3<ref>[https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/19239-mica-levi-under-the-skin-ost/ pitchfork]</ref>\n|rev3=[[Consequence of Sound]]\n\n|rev3score=B+<ref>[https://consequenceofsound.net/2014/04/album-review-mica-levi-under-the-skin-ost/ cos]</ref>\n\n|rev4=Drowned in Sound\n\n|rev4score=8/10<ref>[http://drownedinsound.com/releases/18150/reviews/4147594 dis]</reF>\n\n}}\n[[File:Micachu_at_Crash_Mansion_2008.jpg|thumb|258x258px|[[Micachu|Mica Levi]] performing with Micachu and the Shapes in 2009|left]]\nReleased on March 17, 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/under-the-skin-original-motion-picture-soundtrack-mw0002618596|title=Under the Skin [Original Motion Picture Soundtrack] - Mica Levi {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits {{!}} AllMusic|website=AllMusic|access-date=2018-02-18}}</ref> ''Under the Skin''{{'}}s soundtrack was composed by [[Micachu|Mica Levi]]<ref>{{AllMusic|album|mw0002618596|''Under the Skin {{bracket|Original Motion Picture Soundtrack}}''}} (rating 4/5).</ref><ref>{{Discogs master|674368|Under the Skin}}.</ref> and produced by [[Peter Raeburn]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/mar/15/mica-levi-under-the-skin-soundtrack|title=How Mica Levi got Under The Skin of her first film soundtrack|last=Levi|first=Mica|date=March 15, 2014|website=The Guardian|accessdate=March 1, 2015}}</ref> Raeburn suggested Levi to Glazer, who contacted her after hearing ''Chopped and Screwed'', her collaboration with the [[London Sinfonietta]]. Glazer wanted the music to express the protagonist's feelings as she experienced things like food and sex for the first time, and directed Levi with prompts such as \"What does it sound like to be on fire?\" or \"Imagine when you tell somebody a joke and it\u2019s not very good and their reaction\u2019s a bit stilted\".<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/27/mica-levi-under-the-skin-scarlett-johansson|title=Making music for Scarlett: how an indie composer hit the big time|last=Khomami|first=Nadia|date=27 December 2014|website=The Guardian|accessdate=March 1, 2015}}</ref> Later scenes use less music, to emphasise the sounds of the natural world that Johansson's character experiences.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://filmireland.net/2014/12/23/best-films-of-2014-writers-choices/|title=Best Films of 2014|date=23 December 2014|website=Film Ireland|accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nLevi used mainly a [[viola]] to write and record over ten months, taking inspiration from [[Giacinto Scelsi]], [[Iannis Xenakis]], [[John Cage]] and music played in strip clubs. She looked for the natural and \"identifiably human\" sounds in the instrument, then [[Pitch shift|altered the pitch]] or tempo of her recordings to \"make it feel uncomfortable\".<ref name=\":0\" /> In an article for the ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]],'' Levi wrote: \"Some parts are intended to be quite difficult. If your life force is being distilled by an alien, it's not necessarily going to sound very nice. It's supposed to be physical, alarming, hot.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAccording to ''[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]],'' \"the strings sometimes resemble nails going down a universe-sized chalkboard, screaming with a [[Gy\u00f6rgy Ligeti|Ligeti]]-like sense of horror; elsewhere, they endlessly drone in a gaping vortex, like [[Vangelis]]' iconic [[Blade Runner (soundtrack)|''Blade Runner'' score]] dipped in turpentine.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/interviews/9366-under-the-skins-jonathan-glazer-and-mica-levi/|title=Jonathan Glazer and Mica Levi|last=Fitzmaurice|first=Larry|date=31 March 2014|work=[[Pitchfork Media]]|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> The ''Guardian'' wrote that Levi's \"score brings together strings, percussion, distortions in speed and clashing microphones to create sounds that are seductive, perverted and compassionate.\"<ref name=\":2\" />  In 2019, ''Pitchfork'' ranked the album at number 154 on their list of \"The 200 Best Albums of the 2010s\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/the-200-best-albums-of-the-2010s/|title=The 200 Best Albums of the 2010s|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=8 October 2019|accessdate=9 October 2019}}</ref> They also ranked it 18th on their list of 33 greatest [[industrial music|industrial]] albums of all time.<reF>[https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/the-33-best-industrial-albums-of-all-time/?page=2 pitchfork industrial]</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== Release ==\n=== Box office ===\n''Under the Skin'' [[Film premiere|premiered]] on 29 August 2013 at the [[Telluride Film Festival]]. It was screened at the [[70th Venice International Film Festival]] and the [[2013 Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2013/film/news/toronto-international-film-festival-lineup-1200566779/|title=Toronto Intl. Film Festival Unveils First Batch of Films|last=Punter|first=Jessie|date=23 July 2013|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=16 August 2013|publisher=[[Reed Business Information]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tiff.net/filmsandschedules/festival/2013/undertheskin|title=Under the Skin|work=[[Toronto International Film Festival]]|accessdate=16 August 2013}}</ref> It was released in the [[United Kingdom]] on 14 March 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/news/a531629/scarlett-johanssons-under-the-skin-announces-uk-release-date.html|title=Scarlett Johansson's 'Under the Skin' announces UK release date&nbsp;\u2013 Movies News|date=|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=14 April 2014}}</ref> and the [[United States Army|United States]] on 4 April 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2014/01/under-the-skin-release-date|title=\"Under the Skin\" Scarlett Johansson Alien Movie Release Date|date=7 January 2014|work=Complex|accessdate=14 April 2014}}</ref> ''Under the Skin'' was a box office failure,<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/apr/29/global-box-office-avengers-age-of-ultron-furious-7-cinderella-ex-machina|title=Avengers assemble a potential record-breaker as the Age of Ultron hits|last=Hoad|first=Phil|website=the Guardian|accessdate=2015-05-06}}</ref> grossing $2,614,251 in the United States and Canada<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=main&id=undertheskin2014.htm|title=''Under the Skin'' (2014)|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[Amazon.com|Amazon]]|accessdate=29 December 2014}}</ref> and $4,615,682 in other countries for a worldwide total of $7,229,933, on a production budget of $13.3 million. In the United States, it opened with $140,000 in four theatres; despite earning the highest per-theatre average of all films playing that weekend, above ''[[Captain America: The Winter Soldier]] (''which also stars Johansson),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?view=&yr=2014&wknd=14&p=.htm|title=Weekend Box Office Results for April 4\u20136, 2014|date=|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=14 April 2014}}</ref> it failed to make the list of top-grossing films in the United States speciality box office.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/article/the-30-highest-grossing-indies-of-2014-a-running-list|title=The 30 Highest Grossing Indies of 2014 (A Running List)|date=|work=Indiewire|accessdate=2014-12-29}}</ref> In the United Kingdom, it opened with a gross of \u00a3239,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2014/mar/19/need-for-speed-under-the-skin-uk-box-office|title=Need for Speed in pole position at UK box office but Under the Skin infectious &#124; Film|last=Gant|first=Charles|date=19 March 2014|work=The Guardian|accessdate=14 April 2014}}</ref> According to the ''Guardian'', the film's budget was in \"the danger zone: not in the ultra-low bracket that can make a sharply executed future vision ultra-profitable ... [nor] the $30m-plus range where marketing begins to snag mass audiences.\"<ref name=\":3\" /> ''Under the Skin'' was released on DVD and Blu-ray format on 15 July 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/6550/under-the-skin-2013|title=Under the Skin DVD Release Date July 15, 2014|website=DVDs Release Dates|language=en-US|access-date=2018-02-12}}</ref>\n\n===Reception===\n{{See also|List of accolades received by Under the Skin}}\nThe [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives ''Under the Skin'' an approval rating of 85% based on reviews from 240 critics and an [[average rating]] of 7.85/10. The website's critical consensus states: \"Its message may prove elusive for some, but with absorbing imagery and a mesmerizing performance from Scarlett Johansson, ''Under the Skin'' is a haunting viewing experience.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/under_the_skin_2013/|title=Under the Skin (2013)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=30 May 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], which assigns a rating out of 100 top reviews from mainstream critics, the film has a score of 78 out of 100 based on 42 reviews, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/under-the-skin|title=Under the Skin Reviews|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=20 April 2014}}</ref> Metacritic also listed the film as the fourth best of 2014 based on its appearance in critics' top-ten lists.<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/film-critic-top-10-lists-best-movies-of-2014|title=Film Critic Top 10 Lists - Best Movies of 2014|last=Dietz|first=Jason|date=6 December 2014|website=Metacritic|accessdate=8 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nXan Brooks of the ''Guardian'' gave ''Under the Skin'' five out of five and called it \"far and away the best picture\" in the [[Venice Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/sep/03/under-the-skin-review|title=Under the Skin&nbsp;\u2013 Venice 2013: first look review|last=Brooks|first=Xan|date=9 February 2013|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=4 September 2013|location=London}}</ref> [[Peter Bradshaw]], also of the ''Guardian'', said the film was \"visually stunning and deeply disturbing\" and also awarded it five out of five.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/mar/13/under-the-skin-scarlett-johansson-peter-bradshaw|title=Under the Skin review&nbsp;\u2013 'Very erotic, very scary'|date=13 March 2014|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=15 March 2014|location=London}}</ref> [[Robbie Collin]] of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' wrote: \"If my legs hadn't been so wobbly and my mouth so dry, I would have climbed up on my seat and cheered.\"<ref name=\":6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/venice-film-festival/10283407/Under-the-Skin-Venice-Film-Festival-review.html|title=Under the Skin, Venice Film Festival, review|date=9 April 2013|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=4 September 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130906050111/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/venice-film-festival/10283407/Under-the-Skin-Venice-Film-Festival-review.html|archivedate=6 September 2013|url-status=dead|location=London}}</ref> [[Matt Zoller Seitz]] gave the film four out of four, describing it as \"hideously beautiful. Its life force is overwhelming.\"<ref name=\"Matt ZS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/under-the-skin-2014|title=Under the Skin|author=Zoller Seitz, Matt|date=23 April 2014|work=RogerEbert.com|accessdate=7 January 2015}}</ref> [[Richard Roeper]] gave the film an A+ and four out of four, stating: \"This is what we talk about when we talk about film as art.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suntimes.com/entertainment/movies/26702814-421/under-the-skin-brilliant-mood-piece-about-a-fascinating-femme-fatale.html#.U1WNdNzdCa4 |title=\u2018Under the Skin\u2019: Brilliant mood piece about a fascinating femme fatale |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=22 May 2014|accessdate=10 April 2018}}{{dead link|fix-attempted=yes|date=April 2018}}</ref> [[Christy Lemire]] gave it four out of four, calling it an \"undeniably haunting, singular experience\" and one of the best films of 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://christylemire.com/skin/ |title=Under the Skin |first=Christy |last=Lemire |publisher=Christy Lemire |date=5 April 2014|accessdate=10 April 2018}}</ref> Jon Espino of the Young Folks gave it nine out of ten and called it \"easily one of the most visually haunting films of 2014.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theyoungfolks.com/review/jons-movie-review-under-the-skin-penetrates-deeper-than-just-the-skin/30252|title=Jon's Movie Review: 'Under The Skin' Penetrates Deeper Than Just The Skin|last=Estrada|first=Stephanie|date=2014-04-05|work=The Young Folks|accessdate=2014-08-21}}</ref> Andrew Lowry of ''[[Total Film]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.totalfilm.com/reviews/cinema/under-the-skin-1|title=Under the Skin|work=[[Total Film]]|accessdate=15 March 2014}}</ref> Dave Calhoun of ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeout.com/london/film/under-the-skin-2014|title=Under the Skin|date=12 March 2014|work=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]|accessdate=15 March 2014}}</ref> Kate Muir of ''[[The Times]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/arts/film/reviews/article4032244.ece|title=Under the Skin|date=14 March 2014|work=[[The Times]]|accessdate=15 March 2014}}</ref> and [[Robbie Collin]] of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''<ref name=\":6\" /> each gave the film five out of five.\n\nHowever, Todd McCarthy of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' said that \"the film provides too little for even relatively adventurous specialized audiences to latch onto.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/movie/under-skin/review/627838|title=Under The Skin (2014)|last=McCarthy|first=Todd|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=15 March 2014}}</ref> Kaleem Aftab of ''[[The Independent]]'' stated in his review that \"Glazer simply gave up on trying to find a cohesive story.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/review-under-the-skin--even-scarlett-johansson-cant-save-jonathan-glazers-laughably-bad-alien-hitchhiker-movie-8796596.html|title=Review: Under the Skin&nbsp;\u2013 Even Scarlett Johansson can't save Jonathan Glazer's laughably bad alien hitchhiker movie|last=Aftab|first=Kaleem|date=29 July 2013|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=4 September 2013|location=London}}</ref> Henry Fitzherbert of ''[[The Daily Express]]'' awarded it two out of five and wrote: \"it didn't get under my skin, just on my nerves.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/films/464500/Under-The-Skin-review-and-trailer|title=Under The Skin&nbsp;\u2014 review and trailer|date=12 March 2014|work=[[The Daily Express]]|accessdate=15 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n''Under the Skin'' was named the best film of 2014 by 20 critics and publications.<ref name=\"Metacritic\" /> In 2015, the ''Guardian'' named it one of the top 50 films of the decade so far.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/jan/05/top-50-films-of-the-demi-decade-peter-bradshaw|title=Peter Bradshaw\u2019s top 50 films of the demi-decade|last=Bradshaw|first=Peter|date=5 January 2015|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref> It [[List of accolades received by Under the Skin (2013 film)|received multiple accolades]], including the [[London Film Critics' Circle|London Film Critics Circle]] award for British Film of the Year<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/news/story.asp?NID=43188|title=Boyhood Takes Three At The London Critics' Circle Film Awards|last=White|first=White|date=18 January 2015|work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|accessdate=11 April 2015}}</ref> and a [[European Film Award]] for best soundtrack.<ref name=\":2\" /> In 2016, it was ranked number 61 in the [[BBC's 100 Greatest Films of the 21st Century]],&nbsp;an international poll of 177 critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20160819-the-21st-centurys-100-greatest-films|title=The 21st Century\u2019s 100 greatest films|last=2017|first=18 April|publisher=}}</ref> In France the prestigious [[Cahiers du cin\u00e9ma]] placed Under the Skin on the third place of their 2014 Top Ten chart (just after  [[P'tit Quinquin (film)|P'tit Quinquin]]  and  [[Goodbye to Language]]).<ref>{{cite web|work=Cahiers du cinema|url=https://www.cahiersducinema.com/produit/top-ten-2014|title=Top Ten 2014, Decembre 2014 n\u00b0706}}</ref> It was ranked the fourth best film since 2000 by the critics of ''[[The Guardian]]'', with Andrew Pulver writing: \u201cFrom its unnerving alien-POV sequences, to the empathetic scene with actor Adam Pearson (who has neurofibromatosis), to the sheer coldness of the predatory logic of its central figure, ''Under the Skin'' achieves a mood and texture unlike anything else before or since.\"<ref name=\":14\" /> In 2019, it was named the greatest film of the 2010s by [[Robbie Collin]] of [[The Daily Telegraph]]<ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/0/robbie-collins-films-decade-belong-disney-netflix-now/</ref> and [[Little White Lies]],<ref>https://lwlies.com/articles/the-100-best-films-of-the-decade/</ref> the 2nd greatest by [[Indiewire]] and [[the Irish Times]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/gallery/best-movies-of-2010s-decade/|title=The 100 Best Movies of the Decade|last=Zilko|first=David Ehrlich,Eric Kohn,Kate Erbland,Anne Thompson,Zack Sharf,Chris O'Falt,Jude Dry,Tambay Obenson,Christian Blauvelt,Leah Lu,Christian|last2=Ehrlich|first2=David|date=2019-07-22|website=IndieWire|language=en|access-date=2019-12-24|last3=Kohn|first3=Eric|last4=Erbland|first4=Kate|last5=Thompson|first5=Anne|last6=Sharf|first6=Zack|last7=O'Falt|first7=Chris|last8=Dry|first8=Jude|last9=Obenson|first9=Tambay}}</ref><ref>https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/film/the-25-best-films-of-the-2010s-none-of-them-won-best-picture-oscar-1.4116777?mode=amp</ref> the 11th greatest by [[The A.V. Club]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://film.avclub.com/the-100-best-movies-of-the-2010s-1839846306|title=The A.V. Club's 100 best movies of the 2010s|last=Club|first=The A. V.|website=Film|language=en-us|access-date=2019-12-24}}</ref> and the 56th greatest by [[Film School Rejects]].<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/sep/13/100-best-films-movies-of-the-21st-century|title=The 100 best films of the 21st century|last=Bradshaw|first=Peter|date=2019-09-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-03|last2=Clarke|first2=Cath|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|last3=Pulver|first3=Andrew|last4=Shoard|first4=Catherine}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, [[McFarland & Co.]] Publishers released the book ''Alien in the Mirror: Scarlett Johansson, Jonathan Glazer, and Under the Skin''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Foster|first=Maureen|title=Alien in the Mirror: Scarlett Johansson, Jonathan Glazer, and Under the Skin|publisher=McFarland & Co. Inc.|year=2019|isbn=978-1-4766-7042-3|location=Jefferson, NC USA|pages=}}</ref> by author Maureen Foster.  The book is a scene-by-scene and behind-the-scenes look at the film's narrative, its production and post-production, and its connection to other science fiction cinema depictions of alien life.\n\n=== TV series ===\nIn 2020, ''[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]]'' reported that a television series based on the film was in development.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/jonathan-glazer-jim-wilson-silver-reel-under-the-skin-1202825668/|title=\u2018Under The Skin\u2019: A24 & Silver Reel In Bidding War For TV Rights To Jonathan Glazer\u2019s Cult Sci-Fi Film|last=Kanter|first=Jake|last2=Kanter|first2=Jake|date=2020-01-28|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n== Themes ==\nWriting for the ''[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]'', Duane Dudek speculated that Johansson's character assumes a human identity to collect information about humans as an alien intelligence might, inducing an identity crisis causing her to \"spin out of control like a broken machine\". He wrote that the motorcyclist can be interpreted as a companion, enabler, or pursuer, and that the \"tar-dark world\" where the woman submerges her victims may be a nest, a web, another planet or dimension, or a visual representation of how sex feels to her or them.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jsonline.com/entertainment/movies/under-the-skin-with-scarlett-johansson-confounding-captivating-b99269582z1-259400161.html|title='Under the Skin,' with Scarlett Johansson, confounding, captivating|last=Dudek|first=Duane|date=15 May 2014|newspaper=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref> In the ''Guardian'', Leo Robson wrote that ''Under the Skin'' deals with race and immigration. He interpreted Johansson's character as a \"kind of immigrant\", and that the film's title \"seems like part of an anti-racial slogan, a reminder that despite our racial or ethnic differences we share some basic components\".<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/mar/15/scarlett-johansson-under-skin-extraterrestrial|title=Scarlett Johansson in Under the Skin: 'prick her and she doesn't bleed'|last=Robson|first=Leo|website=the Guardian|accessdate=2015-07-29}}</ref>\n\nThough Glazer said he wanted to make a film \"more about a human experience than a gender experience\",<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/prospero/2014/03/qa-jonathan-glazer|title=Under his skin|date=13 March 2014|newspaper=The Economist|access-date=2015-07-29|issn=0013-0613}}</ref> several critics identified [[Feminism|feminist]] and gender themes. The ''Economist'' wrote that \"there is some aggressive sexuality in the film: women seem very vulnerable but then men\u2019s desires are punished.\"<ref name=\":5\" /> In [[The Mary Sue]], Kristy Puchko wrote that ''Under the Skin'' \"creates a reverse of contemporary [[rape culture]] where violence against women is so common that women are casually warned to be ever alert for those who might harm them ... By and large men don't worry about their safety in the same way when walking home late at night. But in the world of ''Under the Skin'', they absolutely should.\"<ref name=\"MarySue\">{{cite news|url=http://www.themarysue.com/review-under-the-skin/|title=Review: Scarlett Johansson's ''Under the Skin'' has a special message for men|last=Puchko|first=Kristy|date=April 4, 2014|accessdate=April 6, 2010|publisher=TheMarySue.com}}</ref>\n\nRobson wrote that Johansson's character is \"both a watcher and predator of men. In the society she enters, and to which she brings nothing besides a body, [she] is a sex object, in dress and demeanour a kind of sex toy; she might have come to Earth to prove a point about male expectations of women ... If ''Under the Skin'' communicates any gender-politics message, it does so through the disparity in excitement between the male characters' reaction to [Johansson] and that of the camera.\"<ref name=\":4\" /> Noah Gittell, discussing in ''[[The Atlantic]]'' the scene in which Johansson's character undresses before a mirror, wrote: \"You would think the first nude scene by a Hollywood star whose body has been the subject of such intense scrutiny would be big news. But the way the film frames it \u2014 with Johansson having removed almost all of her personality from the character \u2014 it doesn\u2019t play as even remotely sexual, and the scene, remarkably, barely attracted any hype.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2014/07/what-in-the-world-is-scarlett-johansson-up-to-lucy-under-the-skin-her-a-feminist-disappearing-act/375141/|title=What in the World Is Scarlett Johansson Up To?|accessdate=2015-07-31}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\nFlorian Auerochs: Planetarisch, dysphorisch, nonhuman: Michel Fabers \u203aWeltenwanderin\u2039 in Jonathan Glazers UNDER THE SKIN. In: J\u00f6rn Glasenapp (Hg.): Weltliteratur des Kinos. Wilhelm Fink Verlag, Paderborn 2016, {{ISBN|978-3-7705-6050-9}}, S. 263\u2013288. (German)\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://undertheskinmovie.com}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n* {{mojo title|undertheskin2014}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|under_the_skin_2013}}\n* {{metacritic film|under-the-skin}}\n* {{AllMovie title|585953}} (rating 4/5)\n* {{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-26559813|title=Scarlett Johansson on playing 'unscripted' scavenging alien|last=Jones|first=Emma|date=16 March 2014|work=Entertainment & Art|publisher=BBC|authorlink=Emma Jones (journalist)}}\n{{London Film Critics Circle Award for British Film of the Year}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Under The Skin}}\n[[Category:2013 films]]\n[[Category:2010s science fiction films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British science fiction films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction films]]\n[[Category:Swiss films]]\n[[Category:Swiss speculative fiction films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jonathan Glazer]]\n[[Category:Films set in Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Films shot in East Lothian]]\n[[Category:Films based on British novels]]\n[[Category:Film4 Productions films]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Under the Skin (1997 film)}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Under the Skin\n| image = Under the Skin poster.png\n| alt =\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Jonathan Glazer]]\n| producer       = {{plainlist|\n* James Wilson\n* [[Nick Wechsler (producer)|Nick Wechsler]]\n|}}\n| screenplay     = {{plainlist|\n* Walter Campbell\n* Jonathan Glazer\n|}}\n| based on       = {{based on|''[[Under the Skin (novel)|Under the Skin]]''|[[Michel Faber]]}}\n| starring       = [[Scarlett Johansson]]\n| music          = [[Micachu|Mica Levi]]\n| cinematography = [[Daniel Landin]]\n| editing        = Paul Watts\n| studio         = {{plainlist|\n* [[British Film Institute|BFI]]\n* [[Film4]]\n}}\n| distributor    = {{plainlist|\n* [[StudioCanal]] {{small|(UK)}}\n* [[A24 (company)|A24]] {{small|(US)}}\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2013|08|29|[[Telluride Film Festival|Telluride]]|2014|03|14|UK|2014|04|04|US}}\n| runtime        = 108 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 107:59--><ref>{{cite web|title=''UNDER THE SKIN'' (15)|url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/under-skin-film|work=[[British Board of Film Classification]]|date=3 January 2014|accessdate=11 April 2014}}</ref>\n| country        = {{plainlist|\n* United Kingdom<ref name=bfi>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b8b0e572a|title=Under the Skin (2014)|work=[[British Film Institute]]|accessdate=21 August 2017}}</ref>\n* United States<ref name=bfi/>\n* Switzerland<ref name=bfi/>\n|}}\n| language       = English\n| budget         = [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]8 million<br />([[United States dollar|$]]13.3 million)<ref name=\"SD\" >{{cite web|last=Wiseman |first=Andreas |url=http://www.screendaily.com/features/under-the-skin-at-any-cost/5069904.article |title=Under The Skin: at any cost &#124; Features &#124; Screen |work=[[Screen Daily]] |date=24 March 2014 |accessdate=14 April 2014}}</ref>\n| gross          = \u00a35.2 million <br />($7.2 million)<ref name=\"TN\" >{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Under-the-Skin#tab=summary |title=''Under the Skin'' (2014)|work=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|publisher=Nash Information Services, LLC|accessdate=13 November 2016}}</ref>\n}}'''''Under the Skin''''' is a 2013 <!-- Per Wikipedia's film guidelines, do not say British-American, unless so deemed. --> [[science fiction film]] <!-- Please don't add additional genres - we should only have the main genre, as per [[WP:FILMLEAD]] -->directed by [[Jonathan Glazer]] with a screenplay by Glazer and Walter Campbell. The film is loosely based on the [[Under the Skin (novel)|2000 novel]] by [[Michel Faber]]. It stars [[Scarlett Johansson]] as an otherworldly woman who preys on men in [[Scotland]]. The film premiered at [[Telluride Film Festival]] on 29 August 2013. It was released in the UK on 14 March 2014 and the United States on 4 April 2014.\n\nGlazer developed ''Under the Skin'' for over a decade; he and co-screenwriter Walter Campbell pared it back from an elaborate, special effects-heavy concept to a sparse story focusing on an alien perspective of the human world. Most characters were played by non-actors, and many scenes were filmed with [[hidden camera]]s.\n\nWith a total worldwide gross of \u00a35.2 million,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=undertheskin2014.htm|title=Under the Skin (2014) (2014) - Box Office Mojo|website=www.boxofficemojo.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-29}}</ref> ''Under the Skin'' was a [[Box office bomb|box office failure]]. Nevertheless, it received critical acclaim, particularly for Johansson's performance, Glazer's direction, and [[Micachu|Mica Levi]]'s score. It received [[List of accolades received by Under the Skin (2013 film)|multiple awards]] and was named one of the best films of the year and the decade by several publications. It ranks 61st on the [[BBC's 100 Greatest Films of the 21st Century]] list.\n\n== Plot ==<!-- Per WP:FILMPLOT, film summaries must be between 400 and 700  words. Please don't add unnecessary detail. -->\nIn [[Glasgow]], a motorcyclist ([[Jeremy McWilliams]]) retrieves an inert young woman (Lynsey Taylor Mackay) from the roadside and places her in the back of a van, where a naked woman ([[Scarlett Johansson]]) dons her clothes. After buying clothes and make-up at a shopping centre, the woman drives the van around Scotland, picking up men. She lures a man (Joe Szula) into a dilapidated house. As he undresses, following the woman into a void, he is submerged in a liquid abyss.\n\nAt a beach, the woman attempts to pick up a swimmer ([[Kry\u0161tof H\u00e1dek]]), but is interrupted by the cries of a drowning couple. The swimmer rescues the husband, but the husband rushes back into the water to save his wife and both drown. As the swimmer lies exhausted on the beach, the woman strikes his head with a rock, drags him to the van, and drives away, ignoring the couple's distraught baby. Later that night, the motorcyclist retrieves the swimmer's belongings, ignoring the baby, who is still on the beach.\n\nThe woman visits a nightclub and picks up another man ([[Paul Brannigan]]). At the house, he follows her into the void and is submerged in the liquid. Suspended beneath the surface, he sees the swimmer floating naked beside him, alive but bloated and almost immobile. When he reaches to touch him, the swimmer's body collapses and a red mass empties through a trough.\n\nThe next day, the woman receives a rose from a street vendor, purchased from another man in traffic. She then listens to a radio report about the missing family from the beach. The woman then seduces a lonely man with facial disfigurement ([[Adam Pearson (actor)|Adam Pearson]]) but lets him leave after examining herself in a mirror. The motorcyclist intercepts the man and bundles him into a car, then sets out in pursuit of the woman with three other motorcyclists.\n\nIn the [[Scottish Highlands]], the woman abandons the van in the fog. She walks to a restaurant and attempts to eat cake, but retches and spits it out. At a bus stop, she meets a man (Michael Moreland) who offers to help her. At his house, he prepares a meal for her and they watch television. Alone in her room, she examines her body in a mirror. They visit a ruined castle, where the man carries her over a puddle and helps her down some steps. At his house, they kiss and begin to have sex, but the woman stops and examines her genitals.\n\nWandering in a forest, the woman meets a commercial logger (Dave Acton) and shelters in a [[bothy]]. She awakes to find the logger molesting her. She runs into the wilderness but he catches and attempts to rape her; he tears her skin, revealing a black, featureless body. As the woman extricates herself from her skin, the man douses her in fuel and burns her alive. Elsewhere, the motorcyclist stands on a mountaintop and looks out across a snowy field.\n\n== Production ==\n=== Pre-production ===\nDirector [[Jonathan Glazer]] decided to adapt [[Michel Faber]]'s novel ''[[Under the Skin (novel)|Under the Skin]]'' (2000) after finishing his debut film ''[[Sexy Beast]]'' (2000), but work did not begin until he had finished his second film, ''[[Birth (film)|Birth]]'' (2004).<ref name=\":11\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/mar/06/under-the-skin-director-jonathan-glazer-scarlett-johansson|title=Under the Skin: why did this chilling masterpiece take a decade? |last=Leigh |first=Danny | date=2014-03-06 | website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-01-29}}</ref> Glazer's producer James Wilson sent him a script that closely adapted the novel; Glazer admired the script but had no interest in filming it, saying: \"I knew then that I absolutely didn't want to film the book. But I still wanted to make the book a film.\"<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nGlazer and co-writer Milo Addica, later replaced by Walter Campbell, spent several years writing and rewriting the story. They conceived an elaborate high-budget film, and produced a script about two aliens disguised as husband-and-wife farmers. [[Brad Pitt]] was cast as the husband, but progress was slow.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/mar/06/under-the-skin-director-jonathan-glazer-scarlett-johansson|title=Under the Skin: why did this chilling masterpiece take a decade?|last1=Leigh|first1=Danna|date=6 March 2014|website=The Guardian|accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref> Glazer eventually decided to make a film that represented an alien perspective of the human world and focused only on the female character.<ref name=\":7\" /> He and Campbell deleted every scene in their script that did not involve her and deleted the elaborate special effects sequences, a process Glazer likened to \"a big, extravagant rock band turning into [[PJ Harvey]]\".<ref name=\":7\" /> The film also removes the character names.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/artsandculture/article/19230/1/how-to-write-a-minimal-masterpiece-script|title=How to write a minimal masterpiece script|first=|last=Dazed|date=12 March 2014|publisher=|accessdate=8 May 2018}}</ref> Whereas the novel is explicit that the main character is an alien processing humans for meat, the film is more ambiguous.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite news|url=https://uproxx.com/hitfix/did-scarlett-johansson-really-walk-around-scotland-unnoticed-filming-under-the-skin/|title=Did Scarlett Johansson really walk around Scotland unnoticed filming \u2018Under the Skin?\u2019|date=2014-04-07|work=UPROXX|access-date=2018-07-21|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nGlazer shot commercials while the film was in pre-production, which he used to \"sketch\" ideas and test equipment.<ref name=\":8\">{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2014/10/why-jonathan-glazers-under-the-skin-took-a-decade-to-make-videos-190464/|title=Why Jonathan Glazer\u2019s \u2018Under the Skin\u2019 Took a Decade to Make (VIDEOS)|last1=Thompson|first1=Anne|date=23 October 2014|website=IndieWire|accessdate=3 November 2016}}</ref> ''Under the Skin'' was jointly financed by [[Film4 Productions]], the [[British Film Institute]], [[Scottish Screen]], Silver Reel, and [[FilmNation Entertainment]]. Glazer secured final backing after cutting the elaborate special effects scenes from the script.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n=== Casting ===\n[[Gemma Arterton]],<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/gemma-arterton-on-the-voices-and-why-shes-turned-her-back-on-hollywood-10114571.html|title=Gemma Arterton on black comedy The Voices and why she's turned her back on Hollywood|last=Aftab|first=Kaleem|date=17 March 2015|accessdate=1 April 2015|location=London|website=The Independent}}</ref> [[Eva Green]], [[January Jones]], [[Abbie Cornish]] and [[Olivia Wilde]] were considered for the lead.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/film/jonathan-glazer-the-joy-of-division-1.1715260?page=1|title=Jonathan Glazer: the joy of division|newspaper=The Irish Times|access-date=2016-11-03|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2015, Arterton stated that she had been Glazer's first choice but the film had needed a bigger star to get funding.<ref name=\":10\" /> The role went to [[Scarlett Johansson]], who remained committed to the project for four years before it reached completion.<ref name=\":8\" /> Johansson was well known for her roles in [[Blockbuster (entertainment)|blockbuster]] films such as the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] franchise. Glazer said: \"It made a great deal of sense to cast somebody very well known out of context. I remember seeing her walking along the street in a pink jumper on a long lens and she looks like an exotic insect on the wrong continent.\"<ref name=\":9\" /> Despite her fame, Johansson was rarely recognised, as members of the public did not believe it could be her.<ref name=\":9\" /> For the role she learnt to drive a van and master an English accent.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nChampionship motorcycle [[Road racing|road racer]] [[Jeremy McWilliams]] was cast as the motorcyclist, as the film required a \"world-class\" motorcyclist who could ride through the Scottish Highlands at high speeds in bad weather. The logger was played by the owner of a location researched for the film.<ref name=\"film4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.film4.com/special-features/interviews/under-the-skin-casting|title=Under The Skin: Casting|website=Film 4|accessdate=28 June 2014}}</ref> For the man with disfigurement, Glazer did not want to use [[Craniofacial prosthesis|prosthetics]]. To cast the role, the production team contacted the charity [[Changing Faces (charity)|Changing Faces]], which supports people with facial disfigurements. The role went to [[Adam Pearson (actor)|Adam Pearson]], who has [[neurofibromatosis]] and had worked in television productions. Pearson's suggestions about how Johansson's character could lure his character were used in the script.<ref name=\"film4\" />\n\n=== Filming ===\n[[File:Tantallon_castle_1.jpg|thumb|242x242px|Parts of ''Under the Skin'' were shot at [[Tantallon Castle]] in [[East Lothian]], Scotland.<ref>(2015) '''Filmed here - 2012, Under The Skin, Jonathan Glazer''' Film Edinburgh, Retrieved 20 February 2015</ref>]]As Glazer wanted the film to feel realistic,<ref name=\":7\" /> most characters were played by non-actors. Many scenes, such as those set in the nightclub and shopping centre, and the scenes in which Johansson's character picks up men in the van, were unscripted sequences filmed with [[hidden camera]]s.<ref name=\":12\"/><ref name=\":13\" /> The production team would inform the subjects they had been filmed and ask permission to use the footage.<ref name=\":12\" /> Glazer said the men were \"talked through what extremes they would have to go to if they agreed to take part in the film once they understood what we were doing\".<ref name=\":13\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-26559813|title=Scarlett Johansson on playing 'unscripted' scavenging alien|last1=Jones|first1=Emma|date=16 March 2014|accessdate=17 March 2014|publisher=BBC|website=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nThe crew built their own cameras to shoot some scenes.<ref name=\":8\" /> Johansson drove the van with the crew inside, and towed a trailer containing a generator for their equipment.<ref name=\":12\"/> To create the black room in which the character traps men, the crew built a bespoke set with a reflective floor, blackout, and custom lighting. The actors were filmed walking into a pool whose floor sank as they walked, submerging them. The scenes were finished with [[computer graphics]].<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n\n{{album ratings\n\n|rev1=[[Allmusic]]\n\n|rev1score={{rating|5|5}}<ref>[https://www.allmusic.com/album/under-the-skin-original-motion-picture-soundtrack-mw0002618596 Allmusic]</ref>\n\n|rev2=[[Pitchfork (magazine)|Pitchfork]]\n\n|rev2score=7.3<ref>[https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/19239-mica-levi-under-the-skin-ost/ pitchfork]</ref>\n|rev3=[[Consequence of Sound]]\n\n|rev3score=B+<ref>[https://consequenceofsound.net/2014/04/album-review-mica-levi-under-the-skin-ost/ cos]</ref>\n\n|rev4=Drowned in Sound\n\n|rev4score=8/10<ref>[http://drownedinsound.com/releases/18150/reviews/4147594 dis]</reF>\n\n}}\n[[File:Micachu_at_Crash_Mansion_2008.jpg|thumb|258x258px|[[Micachu|Mica Levi]] performing with Micachu and the Shapes in 2009|left]]\nReleased on March 17, 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/under-the-skin-original-motion-picture-soundtrack-mw0002618596|title=Under the Skin [Original Motion Picture Soundtrack] - Mica Levi {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits {{!}} AllMusic|website=AllMusic|access-date=2018-02-18}}</ref> ''Under the Skin''{{'}}s soundtrack was composed by [[Micachu|Mica Levi]]<ref>{{AllMusic|album|mw0002618596|''Under the Skin {{bracket|Original Motion Picture Soundtrack}}''}} (rating 4/5).</ref><ref>{{Discogs master|674368|Under the Skin}}.</ref> and produced by [[Peter Raeburn]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/mar/15/mica-levi-under-the-skin-soundtrack|title=How Mica Levi got Under The Skin of her first film soundtrack|last=Levi|first=Mica|date=March 15, 2014|website=The Guardian|accessdate=March 1, 2015}}</ref> Raeburn suggested Levi to Glazer, who contacted her after hearing ''Chopped and Screwed'', her collaboration with the [[London Sinfonietta]]. Glazer wanted the music to express the protagonist's feelings as she experienced things like food and sex for the first time, and directed Levi with prompts such as \"What does it sound like to be on fire?\" or \"Imagine when you tell somebody a joke and it\u2019s not very good and their reaction\u2019s a bit stilted\".<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/27/mica-levi-under-the-skin-scarlett-johansson|title=Making music for Scarlett: how an indie composer hit the big time|last=Khomami|first=Nadia|date=27 December 2014|website=The Guardian|accessdate=March 1, 2015}}</ref> Later scenes use less music, to emphasise the sounds of the natural world that Johansson's character experiences.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://filmireland.net/2014/12/23/best-films-of-2014-writers-choices/|title=Best Films of 2014|date=23 December 2014|website=Film Ireland|accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nLevi used mainly a [[viola]] to write and record over ten months, taking inspiration from [[Giacinto Scelsi]], [[Iannis Xenakis]], [[John Cage]] and music played in strip clubs. She looked for the natural and \"identifiably human\" sounds in the instrument, then [[Pitch shift|altered the pitch]] or tempo of her recordings to \"make it feel uncomfortable\".<ref name=\":0\" /> In an article for the ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]],'' Levi wrote: \"Some parts are intended to be quite difficult. If your life force is being distilled by an alien, it's not necessarily going to sound very nice. It's supposed to be physical, alarming, hot.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAccording to ''[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]],'' \"the strings sometimes resemble nails going down a universe-sized chalkboard, screaming with a [[Gy\u00f6rgy Ligeti|Ligeti]]-like sense of horror; elsewhere, they endlessly drone in a gaping vortex, like [[Vangelis]]' iconic [[Blade Runner (soundtrack)|''Blade Runner'' score]] dipped in turpentine.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/interviews/9366-under-the-skins-jonathan-glazer-and-mica-levi/|title=Jonathan Glazer and Mica Levi|last=Fitzmaurice|first=Larry|date=31 March 2014|work=[[Pitchfork Media]]|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> The ''Guardian'' wrote that Levi's \"score brings together strings, percussion, distortions in speed and clashing microphones to create sounds that are seductive, perverted and compassionate.\"<ref name=\":2\" />  In 2019, ''Pitchfork'' ranked the album at number 154 on their list of \"The 200 Best Albums of the 2010s\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/the-200-best-albums-of-the-2010s/|title=The 200 Best Albums of the 2010s|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=8 October 2019|accessdate=9 October 2019}}</ref> They also ranked it 18th on their list of 33 greatest [[industrial music|industrial]] albums of all time.<reF>[https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/the-33-best-industrial-albums-of-all-time/?page=2 pitchfork industrial]</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== Release ==\n=== Box office ===\n''Under the Skin'' [[Film premiere|premiered]] on 29 August 2013 at the [[Telluride Film Festival]]. It was screened at the [[70th Venice International Film Festival]] and the [[2013 Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2013/film/news/toronto-international-film-festival-lineup-1200566779/|title=Toronto Intl. Film Festival Unveils First Batch of Films|last=Punter|first=Jessie|date=23 July 2013|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=16 August 2013|publisher=[[Reed Business Information]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tiff.net/filmsandschedules/festival/2013/undertheskin|title=Under the Skin|work=[[Toronto International Film Festival]]|accessdate=16 August 2013}}</ref> It was released in the [[United Kingdom]] on 14 March 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/news/a531629/scarlett-johanssons-under-the-skin-announces-uk-release-date.html|title=Scarlett Johansson's 'Under the Skin' announces UK release date&nbsp;\u2013 Movies News|date=|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=14 April 2014}}</ref> and the [[United States Army|United States]] on 4 April 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2014/01/under-the-skin-release-date|title=\"Under the Skin\" Scarlett Johansson Alien Movie Release Date|date=7 January 2014|work=Complex|accessdate=14 April 2014}}</ref> ''Under the Skin'' was a box office failure,<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/apr/29/global-box-office-avengers-age-of-ultron-furious-7-cinderella-ex-machina|title=Avengers assemble a potential record-breaker as the Age of Ultron hits|last=Hoad|first=Phil|website=the Guardian|accessdate=2015-05-06}}</ref> grossing $2,614,251 in the United States and Canada<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=main&id=undertheskin2014.htm|title=''Under the Skin'' (2014)|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[Amazon.com|Amazon]]|accessdate=29 December 2014}}</ref> and $4,615,682 in other countries for a worldwide total of $7,229,933, on a production budget of $13.3 million. In the United States, it opened with $140,000 in four theatres; despite earning the highest per-theatre average of all films playing that weekend, above ''[[Captain America: The Winter Soldier]] (''which also stars Johansson),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?view=&yr=2014&wknd=14&p=.htm|title=Weekend Box Office Results for April 4\u20136, 2014|date=|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=14 April 2014}}</ref> it failed to make the list of top-grossing films in the United States speciality box office.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/article/the-30-highest-grossing-indies-of-2014-a-running-list|title=The 30 Highest Grossing Indies of 2014 (A Running List)|date=|work=Indiewire|accessdate=2014-12-29}}</ref> In the United Kingdom, it opened with a gross of \u00a3239,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2014/mar/19/need-for-speed-under-the-skin-uk-box-office|title=Need for Speed in pole position at UK box office but Under the Skin infectious &#124; Film|last=Gant|first=Charles|date=19 March 2014|work=The Guardian|accessdate=14 April 2014}}</ref> According to the ''Guardian'', the film's budget was in \"the danger zone: not in the ultra-low bracket that can make a sharply executed future vision ultra-profitable ... [nor] the $30m-plus range where marketing begins to snag mass audiences.\"<ref name=\":3\" /> ''Under the Skin'' was released on DVD and Blu-ray format on 15 July 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/6550/under-the-skin-2013|title=Under the Skin DVD Release Date July 15, 2014|website=DVDs Release Dates|language=en-US|access-date=2018-02-12}}</ref>\n\n===Reception===\n{{See also|List of accolades received by Under the Skin}}\nThe [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives ''Under the Skin'' an approval rating of 85% based on reviews from 240 critics and an [[average rating]] of 7.85/10. The website's critical consensus states: \"Its message may prove elusive for some, but with absorbing imagery and a mesmerizing performance from Scarlett Johansson, ''Under the Skin'' is a haunting viewing experience.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/under_the_skin_2013/|title=Under the Skin (2013)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=30 May 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], which assigns a rating out of 100 top reviews from mainstream critics, the film has a score of 78 out of 100 based on 42 reviews, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/under-the-skin|title=Under the Skin Reviews|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=20 April 2014}}</ref> Metacritic also listed the film as the fourth best of 2014 based on its appearance in critics' top-ten lists.<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/film-critic-top-10-lists-best-movies-of-2014|title=Film Critic Top 10 Lists - Best Movies of 2014|last=Dietz|first=Jason|date=6 December 2014|website=Metacritic|accessdate=8 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nXan Brooks of the ''Guardian'' gave ''Under the Skin'' five out of five and called it \"far and away the best picture\" in the [[Venice Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/sep/03/under-the-skin-review|title=Under the Skin&nbsp;\u2013 Venice 2013: first look review|last=Brooks|first=Xan|date=9 February 2013|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=4 September 2013|location=London}}</ref> [[Peter Bradshaw]], also of the ''Guardian'', said the film was \"visually stunning and deeply disturbing\" and also awarded it five out of five.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/mar/13/under-the-skin-scarlett-johansson-peter-bradshaw|title=Under the Skin review&nbsp;\u2013 'Very erotic, very scary'|date=13 March 2014|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=15 March 2014|location=London}}</ref> [[Robbie Collin]] of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' wrote: \"If my legs hadn't been so wobbly and my mouth so dry, I would have climbed up on my seat and cheered.\"<ref name=\":6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/venice-film-festival/10283407/Under-the-Skin-Venice-Film-Festival-review.html|title=Under the Skin, Venice Film Festival, review|date=9 April 2013|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=4 September 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130906050111/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/venice-film-festival/10283407/Under-the-Skin-Venice-Film-Festival-review.html|archivedate=6 September 2013|url-status=dead|location=London}}</ref> [[Matt Zoller Seitz]] gave the film four out of four, describing it as \"hideously beautiful. Its life force is overwhelming.\"<ref name=\"Matt ZS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/under-the-skin-2014|title=Under the Skin|author=Zoller Seitz, Matt|date=23 April 2014|work=RogerEbert.com|accessdate=7 January 2015}}</ref> [[Richard Roeper]] gave the film an A+ and four out of four, stating: \"This is what we talk about when we talk about film as art.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suntimes.com/entertainment/movies/26702814-421/under-the-skin-brilliant-mood-piece-about-a-fascinating-femme-fatale.html#.U1WNdNzdCa4 |title=\u2018Under the Skin\u2019: Brilliant mood piece about a fascinating femme fatale |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=22 May 2014|accessdate=10 April 2018}}{{dead link|fix-attempted=yes|date=April 2018}}</ref> [[Christy Lemire]] gave it four out of four, calling it an \"undeniably haunting, singular experience\" and one of the best films of 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://christylemire.com/skin/ |title=Under the Skin |first=Christy |last=Lemire |publisher=Christy Lemire |date=5 April 2014|accessdate=10 April 2018}}</ref> Jon Espino of the Young Folks gave it nine out of ten and called it \"easily one of the most visually haunting films of 2014.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theyoungfolks.com/review/jons-movie-review-under-the-skin-penetrates-deeper-than-just-the-skin/30252|title=Jon's Movie Review: 'Under The Skin' Penetrates Deeper Than Just The Skin|last=Estrada|first=Stephanie|date=2014-04-05|work=The Young Folks|accessdate=2014-08-21}}</ref> Andrew Lowry of ''[[Total Film]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.totalfilm.com/reviews/cinema/under-the-skin-1|title=Under the Skin|work=[[Total Film]]|accessdate=15 March 2014}}</ref> Dave Calhoun of ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeout.com/london/film/under-the-skin-2014|title=Under the Skin|date=12 March 2014|work=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]|accessdate=15 March 2014}}</ref> Kate Muir of ''[[The Times]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/arts/film/reviews/article4032244.ece|title=Under the Skin|date=14 March 2014|work=[[The Times]]|accessdate=15 March 2014}}</ref> and [[Robbie Collin]] of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''<ref name=\":6\" /> each gave the film five out of five.\n\nHowever, Todd McCarthy of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' said that \"the film provides too little for even relatively adventurous specialized audiences to latch onto.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/movie/under-skin/review/627838|title=Under The Skin (2014)|last=McCarthy|first=Todd|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=15 March 2014}}</ref> Kaleem Aftab of ''[[The Independent]]'' stated in his review that \"Glazer simply gave up on trying to find a cohesive story.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/review-under-the-skin--even-scarlett-johansson-cant-save-jonathan-glazers-laughably-bad-alien-hitchhiker-movie-8796596.html|title=Review: Under the Skin&nbsp;\u2013 Even Scarlett Johansson can't save Jonathan Glazer's laughably bad alien hitchhiker movie|last=Aftab|first=Kaleem|date=29 July 2013|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=4 September 2013|location=London}}</ref> Henry Fitzherbert of ''[[The Daily Express]]'' awarded it two out of five and wrote: \"it didn't get under my skin, just on my nerves.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/films/464500/Under-The-Skin-review-and-trailer|title=Under The Skin&nbsp;\u2014 review and trailer|date=12 March 2014|work=[[The Daily Express]]|accessdate=15 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n''Under the Skin'' was named the best film of 2014 by 20 critics and publications.<ref name=\"Metacritic\" /> In 2015, the ''Guardian'' named it one of the top 50 films of the decade so far.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/jan/05/top-50-films-of-the-demi-decade-peter-bradshaw|title=Peter Bradshaw\u2019s top 50 films of the demi-decade|last=Bradshaw|first=Peter|date=5 January 2015|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref> It [[List of accolades received by Under the Skin (2013 film)|received multiple accolades]], including the [[London Film Critics' Circle|London Film Critics Circle]] award for British Film of the Year<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/news/story.asp?NID=43188|title=Boyhood Takes Three At The London Critics' Circle Film Awards|last=White|first=White|date=18 January 2015|work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|accessdate=11 April 2015}}</ref> and a [[European Film Award]] for best soundtrack.<ref name=\":2\" /> In 2016, it was ranked number 61 in the [[BBC's 100 Greatest Films of the 21st Century]],&nbsp;an international poll of 177 critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20160819-the-21st-centurys-100-greatest-films|title=The 21st Century\u2019s 100 greatest films|last=2017|first=18 April|publisher=}}</ref> In France the prestigious [[Cahiers du cin\u00e9ma]] placed Under the Skin on the third place of their 2014 Top Ten chart (just after  [[P'tit Quinquin (film)|P'tit Quinquin]]  and  [[Goodbye to Language]]).<ref>{{cite web|work=Cahiers du cinema|url=https://www.cahiersducinema.com/produit/top-ten-2014|title=Top Ten 2014, Decembre 2014 n\u00b0706}}</ref> It was ranked the fourth best film since 2000 by the critics of ''[[The Guardian]]'', with Andrew Pulver writing: \u201cFrom its unnerving alien-POV sequences, to the empathetic scene with actor Adam Pearson (who has neurofibromatosis), to the sheer coldness of the predatory logic of its central figure, ''Under the Skin'' achieves a mood and texture unlike anything else before or since.\"<ref name=\":14\" /> In 2019, it was named the greatest film of the 2010s by [[Robbie Collin]] of [[The Daily Telegraph]]<ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/0/robbie-collins-films-decade-belong-disney-netflix-now/</ref>, the 2nd greatest by [[Indiewire]] and [[the Irish Times]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/gallery/best-movies-of-2010s-decade/|title=The 100 Best Movies of the Decade|last=Zilko|first=David Ehrlich,Eric Kohn,Kate Erbland,Anne Thompson,Zack Sharf,Chris O'Falt,Jude Dry,Tambay Obenson,Christian Blauvelt,Leah Lu,Christian|last2=Ehrlich|first2=David|date=2019-07-22|website=IndieWire|language=en|access-date=2019-12-24|last3=Kohn|first3=Eric|last4=Erbland|first4=Kate|last5=Thompson|first5=Anne|last6=Sharf|first6=Zack|last7=O'Falt|first7=Chris|last8=Dry|first8=Jude|last9=Obenson|first9=Tambay}}</ref><ref>https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/film/the-25-best-films-of-the-2010s-none-of-them-won-best-picture-oscar-1.4116777?mode=amp</ref> the 11th best by [[The A.V. Club]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://film.avclub.com/the-100-best-movies-of-the-2010s-1839846306|title=The A.V. Club's 100 best movies of the 2010s|last=Club|first=The A. V.|website=Film|language=en-us|access-date=2019-12-24}}</ref> and the 56th best by [[Film School Rejects]].<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/sep/13/100-best-films-movies-of-the-21st-century|title=The 100 best films of the 21st century|last=Bradshaw|first=Peter|date=2019-09-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-03|last2=Clarke|first2=Cath|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|last3=Pulver|first3=Andrew|last4=Shoard|first4=Catherine}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, [[McFarland & Co.]] Publishers released the book ''Alien in the Mirror: Scarlett Johansson, Jonathan Glazer, and Under the Skin''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Foster|first=Maureen|title=Alien in the Mirror: Scarlett Johansson, Jonathan Glazer, and Under the Skin|publisher=McFarland & Co. Inc.|year=2019|isbn=978-1-4766-7042-3|location=Jefferson, NC USA|pages=}}</ref> by author Maureen Foster.  The book is a scene-by-scene and behind-the-scenes look at the film's narrative, its production and post-production, and its connection to other science fiction cinema depictions of alien life. \n\n=== TV series ===\nIn 2020, ''[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]]'' reported that a television series based on the film was in development.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/jonathan-glazer-jim-wilson-silver-reel-under-the-skin-1202825668/|title=\u2018Under The Skin\u2019: A24 & Silver Reel In Bidding War For TV Rights To Jonathan Glazer\u2019s Cult Sci-Fi Film|last=Kanter|first=Jake|last2=Kanter|first2=Jake|date=2020-01-28|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n== Themes ==\nWriting for the ''[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]'', Duane Dudek speculated that Johansson's character assumes a human identity to collect information about humans as an alien intelligence might, inducing an identity crisis causing her to \"spin out of control like a broken machine\". He wrote that the motorcyclist can be interpreted as a companion, enabler, or pursuer, and that the \"tar-dark world\" where the woman submerges her victims may be a nest, a web, another planet or dimension, or a visual representation of how sex feels to her or them.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jsonline.com/entertainment/movies/under-the-skin-with-scarlett-johansson-confounding-captivating-b99269582z1-259400161.html|title='Under the Skin,' with Scarlett Johansson, confounding, captivating|last=Dudek|first=Duane|date=15 May 2014|newspaper=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref> In the ''Guardian'', Leo Robson wrote that ''Under the Skin'' deals with race and immigration. He interpreted Johansson's character as a \"kind of immigrant\", and that the film's title \"seems like part of an anti-racial slogan, a reminder that despite our racial or ethnic differences we share some basic components\".<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/mar/15/scarlett-johansson-under-skin-extraterrestrial|title=Scarlett Johansson in Under the Skin: 'prick her and she doesn't bleed'|last=Robson|first=Leo|website=the Guardian|accessdate=2015-07-29}}</ref>\n\nThough Glazer said he wanted to make a film \"more about a human experience than a gender experience\",<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/prospero/2014/03/qa-jonathan-glazer|title=Under his skin|date=13 March 2014|newspaper=The Economist|access-date=2015-07-29|issn=0013-0613}}</ref> several critics identified [[Feminism|feminist]] and gender themes. The ''Economist'' wrote that \"there is some aggressive sexuality in the film: women seem very vulnerable but then men\u2019s desires are punished.\"<ref name=\":5\" /> In [[The Mary Sue]], Kristy Puchko wrote that ''Under the Skin'' \"creates a reverse of contemporary [[rape culture]] where violence against women is so common that women are casually warned to be ever alert for those who might harm them ... By and large men don't worry about their safety in the same way when walking home late at night. But in the world of ''Under the Skin'', they absolutely should.\"<ref name=\"MarySue\">{{cite news|url=http://www.themarysue.com/review-under-the-skin/|title=Review: Scarlett Johansson's ''Under the Skin'' has a special message for men|last=Puchko|first=Kristy|date=April 4, 2014|accessdate=April 6, 2010|publisher=TheMarySue.com}}</ref>\n\nRobson wrote that Johansson's character is \"both a watcher and predator of men. In the society she enters, and to which she brings nothing besides a body, [she] is a sex object, in dress and demeanour a kind of sex toy; she might have come to Earth to prove a point about male expectations of women ... If ''Under the Skin'' communicates any gender-politics message, it does so through the disparity in excitement between the male characters' reaction to [Johansson] and that of the camera.\"<ref name=\":4\" /> Noah Gittell, discussing in ''[[The Atlantic]]'' the scene in which Johansson's character undresses before a mirror, wrote: \"You would think the first nude scene by a Hollywood star whose body has been the subject of such intense scrutiny would be big news. But the way the film frames it \u2014 with Johansson having removed almost all of her personality from the character \u2014 it doesn\u2019t play as even remotely sexual, and the scene, remarkably, barely attracted any hype.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2014/07/what-in-the-world-is-scarlett-johansson-up-to-lucy-under-the-skin-her-a-feminist-disappearing-act/375141/|title=What in the World Is Scarlett Johansson Up To?|accessdate=2015-07-31}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\nFlorian Auerochs: Planetarisch, dysphorisch, nonhuman: Michel Fabers \u203aWeltenwanderin\u2039 in Jonathan Glazers UNDER THE SKIN. In: J\u00f6rn Glasenapp (Hg.): Weltliteratur des Kinos. Wilhelm Fink Verlag, Paderborn 2016, {{ISBN|978-3-7705-6050-9}}, S. 263\u2013288. (German)\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://undertheskinmovie.com}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n* {{mojo title|undertheskin2014}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|under_the_skin_2013}}\n* {{metacritic film|under-the-skin}}\n* {{AllMovie title|585953}} (rating 4/5)\n* {{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-26559813|title=Scarlett Johansson on playing 'unscripted' scavenging alien|last=Jones|first=Emma|date=16 March 2014|work=Entertainment & Art|publisher=BBC|authorlink=Emma Jones (journalist)}}\n{{London Film Critics Circle Award for British Film of the Year}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Under The Skin}}\n[[Category:2013 films]]\n[[Category:2010s science fiction films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British science fiction films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction films]]\n[[Category:Swiss films]]\n[[Category:Swiss speculative fiction films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jonathan Glazer]]\n[[Category:Films set in Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Films shot in East Lothian]]\n[[Category:Films based on British novels]]\n[[Category:Film4 Productions films]]\n", "name_user": "Tommy69mamy4lyfe", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eReception)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Under_the_Skin_(2013_film)"}
{"title_page": "List of Donald Trump 2020 presidential campaign endorsements", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Donald Trump series|expanded=Campaigns }}\nThis is a list of notable<!-- \"Notable\" as in they have a Wikipedia article about them as an individual. Otherwise the list can go on-and-on-and-on with marginally notable persons. --> individuals and organizations who voiced their endorsement for the office of the president of [[Donald Trump]] as the [[2020 Republican Party presidential primaries|Republican Party's presidential candidate]] for the [[2020 United States presidential election]].\n\n==Endorsements==\n===The Republican Party===\nStarting in 1932, when [[Herbert Hoover|President Hoover]] was able to unanimously secure that year's nomination despite losing most primaries, the Republican party has always unofficially supported the incumbent despite remaining officially aloof.{{original research inline|inline|date=February 2019}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/event/United-States-presidential-election-of-1976|title=United States presidential election of 1976 - United States government|website=Encyclopedia Britannica}}</ref> This strategy has not always proven successful, as President [[Gerald Ford]] nearly [[1976 Republican National Convention|lost the nomination]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nationalinterest.org/blog/the-buzz/ronald-reagan-vs-gerald-ford-the-1976-gop-convention-battle-15818|title=Ronald Reagan vs. Gerald Ford: The 1976 GOP Convention Battle Royal|first=Lee|last=Edwards|date=April 16, 2016|website=The National Interest}}</ref> in the 1976 primaries and President [[George H.W. Bush]] was challenged in [[1992 Republican Party presidential primaries|1992]].\n\nIn December 2018, the Trump campaign announced that it was merging its field operations with that of the Republican National Committee's.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/12/18/politics/trump-2020-campaign-rnc/index.html|title=Trump gears up for 2020 re-election by tightening grip on party|author=Dan Merica|website=Cnn.com|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}</ref> The following month at the RNC's winter meeting in New Mexico, while acknowledging that declaring the President the party's provisional nominee would break FEC rules, the RNC voted to endorse him informally by voting to give him its \"full support.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2019/jan/26/rnc-vote-unanimous-support-trump-no-endorse-2020/|title=RNC unanimously pledges 'undivided support' for Trump, stops short of explicit 2020 endorsement|first=Andrew|last=Blake|date=January 26, 2019|publisher=The Washington Times|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== United States presidents ===\n\n===U.S. Executive Branch officials===\n====Current====\n[[File:Mike Pence official Vice Presidential portrait (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|[[Mike Pence]]]]\n[[File:Ben_Carson_official_portrait.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Ben Carson]]]]\n[[File:Nikki Haley official photo.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Nikki Haley]]]]\n* [[Mike Pence]], [[Vice President of the United States]] 2017\u2013present; [[Governor of Indiana|Governor]] of [[Indiana]] 2013\u20132017; [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[Indiana's 6th congressional district|IN-6]] 2001\u20132013<ref name=PenceDecline>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/politics/washington/la-na-essential-washington-updates-pence-deems-report-of-2020-presidential-1502035646-htmlstory.html|title=Vice president vehemently denies laying groundwork for potential 2020 White House bid|date=August 6, 2017|first=Laura|last=King|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Ben Carson]], [[United States Secretary of Housing and Urban Development|U.S. Secretary of Housing and Urban Development]] 2017\u2013present; [[Ben Carson presidential campaign, 2016|candidate]] for President in [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 2016|2016]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/politics/wp/2017/08/23/why-ben-carsons-appearance-in-phoenix-was-likely-a-violation-of-federal-law/|title=Why Ben Carson's appearance in Phoenix was likely a violation of federal law|date=August 23, 2017|first=Philip|last=Bump|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=September 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Former====\n* [[Nikki Haley]], [[U.S. Ambassador to the United Nations]] 2017\u20132018; [[Governor of South Carolina|Governor]] of [[South Carolina]] 2011\u20132017<ref>{{cite web |last1=March |first1=Mary Tyler |title=Haley says she'll campaign for Trump in 2020 |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/410548-haley-says-shell-campaign-for-trump-in-2020 |website=TheHill |language=en |date=October 9, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Steve Bannon]], [[White House Chief Strategist]] in 2017<ref>{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/87b52f8ea4874ed8a408927c12b12149|title=Steve Bannon wants GOP to rally behind Trump|date=August 20, 2018|agency=Associated Press|last1=Lucey|first1=Catherine}}</ref>\n* [[Katie Walsh (politician)|Katie Walsh]], [[White House Deputy Chief of Staff]] for Implementation in 2017<ref name=TrumpFamilyRNC>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2017/05/27/trump-family-members-met-with-gop-leaders-to-discuss-strategy|title=Trump family members met with GOP leaders to discuss strategy|date=May 27, 2017|first=Robert|last=Costa|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=June 19, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[John McEntee (political aide)|John McEntee]], [[Body man|Personal Aide to the President]] 2017\u20132018<ref name=McEnteePierson>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2018/03/trump-2020-campaign-now-accepting-all-white-house-rejects|title=TRUMP 2020 CAMPAIGN NOW ACCEPTING ALL WHITE HOUSE REJECTS|date=March 14, 2018|first=Bess|last=Levin|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|accessdate=March 15, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[George Gigicos]], White House Scheduling and Advance Director in 2017<ref name=GigicosParscale>{{cite web|url