 5th congressional district|OK-5]] 2011\u20132015<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/videos/politics/2018/04/29/sotu-lankford-2020.cnn|title=Lankford backs Trump re-election bid in 2020|date=April 29, 2018|work=[[CNN]]|accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Lindsey Graham]], [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]] from [[South Carolina]] 2003\u2013present; [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[South Carolina's 3rd congressional district|SC-3]] 1995\u20132003; [[Lindsey Graham presidential campaign, 2016|candidate]] for President in [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 2016|2016]]<ref name=GrahamMcMaster>{{cite web|url=https://www.postandcourier.com/politics/lindsey-graham-and-henry-mcmaster-promise-to-back-trump-in/article_82e28d4c-43e8-11e8-80c5-6705797c556d.html|title=Lindsey Graham and Henry McMaster promise to back Trump in 2020 bid|date=April 19, 2018|first=Caitlin|last=Byrd|work=[[The Post and Courier]]|accessdate=April 19, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Lamar Alexander]], [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]] from [[Tennessee]] 2003\u2013present; 45th [[Governor of Tennessee|Governor]] of [[Tennessee]] 1979\u20131987<ref>{{Citation|last=The Hill|title=Alexander supports Trump re-election despite 'inappropriate' Ukraine call|url=https://apple.news/AqM6CTYqPSmesOmf0fvldvA|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref>\n* [[Ted Cruz]], [[United States Senate|U.S Senator]] from [[Texas]] 2013\u2013present; [[Solicitor General of Texas|Solicitor General]] of [[Texas]] 2003\u20132008; [[Ted Cruz presidential campaign, 2016|candidate]] for President in [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 2016|2016]]<ref>{{Citation|last=Fox Business|title=Ted Cruz endorses Trump for 2020 election|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IaCGMPk3JqA|access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref>\n* [[Mike Lee (American politician)|Mike Lee]], [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]] from [[Utah]] 2011\u2013present<ref>{{cite web|url=https://utahpolicy.com/index.php/features/today-at-utah-policy/18888-lee-says-he-will-endorse-president-trump-s-re-election-bid-in-2020|title=Lee says he will endorse President Trump's re-election bid in 2020|date=January 1, 2019|work=Utah Policy|last=Schott|first=Bryan|accessdate=January 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===U.S. Representatives===\n\n====Current====\n* [[Ted Yoho]], [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[Florida's 3rd congressional district|FL-3]] 2013\u2013present<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ocala.com/news/20190620/yoho-eyes-2020-endorses-trump|title=Yoho eyes 2020, endorses Trump|work=[[Star-Banner]]|last=Caplan|first=Andrew|date=June 20, 2019|accessdate=June 21, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Don Bacon (politician)|Don Bacon]], [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[Nebraska's 2nd congressional district|NE-2]] 2017\u2013present<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.omaha.com/news/politics/it-s-an-easy-choice-rep-don-bacon-says-as/article_fa7350ac-f393-5b81-af59-8e352890ea98.html|title='It's an easy choice,' Rep. Don Bacon says as he quickly endorses Donald Trump|work=[[Omaha World-Herald]]|last=Moring|first=Roseann|date=June 19, 2019|accessdate=June 19, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Jeff Van Drew]], [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[New Jersey's 2nd congressional district|NJ-02]] 2019\u2013present<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/12/19/trump-meet-party-switching-van-drew-087976|title=Van Drew pledges 'undying support' for Trump as he switches parties|first=Anita|last=Kumar|website=POLITICO}}</ref> (former Democrat) \n* [[John Katko]], [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[New York's 24th congressional district|NY-24]] 2015\u2013present<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailyorange.com/2020/01/representative-john-katko-endorses-trump-2020/|title=Rep. John Katko endorses Trump for 2020|date=January 26, 2020|first=Chris|last=Hippensteel|work=[[The Daily Orange]]|accessdate=January 27, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Jim Jordan (American politician)|Jim Jordan]], [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[Ohio's 4th congressional district|OH-04]] 2007\u2013present<ref>https://www.nbcnews.com/video/trump-brings-jim-jordan-on-stage-at-ohio-rally...</ref>\n\n===Governors===\n====Current====\n* [[Ron DeSantis]], [[Governor of Florida|Governor]] of [[Florida]] 2019\u2013present<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/410789-rubio-trump-will-be-2020-gop-nominee-and-win-general-election|title=Rubio: Trump will be 2020 GOP nominee and win general election|first=John|last=Bowden|date=October 10, 2018|website=TheHill}}</ref>\n* [[Tate Reeves]], [[Governor of Mississippi|Governor]] of [[Mississippi]] 2020\u2013present<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clarionledger.com/story/news/politics/2019/11/01/ms-election-jim-hood-speaks-tupelo-ahead-trump-visit-reeves/4125551002/|title=Trump is rallying for Tate Reeves in Jim Hood's backyard. Hood said he's not worried.|first1=Luke|last1=Ramseth|first2=Giacomo|last2=Bologna|website=The Clarion Ledger}}</ref>\n* [[Henry McMaster]], [[Governor of South Carolina|Governor]] of [[South Carolina]] 2017\u2013present<ref name=GrahamMcMaster/>\n* [[Greg Abbott]], [[Governor of Texas|Governor]] of [[Texas]] 2015\u2013present<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tilove |first1=Jonathan |title=Calling Texas GOP `the party of results,' Abbott looks to 2020 elections |url=https://www.statesman.com/news/20190608/calling-texas-gop-the-party-of-results-abbott-looks-to-2020-elections |website=Austin American-Statesman |language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Jim Justice]], [[Governor of West Virginia|Governor]] of [[West Virginia]] 2017\u2013present (former Democrat)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://time.com/4886765/west-virginia-rally-jim-justice-republican-trump/|title='I Can't Help You Anymore Being a Democrat.' West Virginia Governor Switches Parties at Trump Rally|date=August 3, 2017|first=Alana|last=Abramson|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n====Former====\