1976|title=United States presidential election of 1976 - United States government|website=Encyclopedia Britannica}}</ref> This strategy has not always proven successful, as President [[Gerald Ford]] nearly [[1976 Republican National Convention|lost the nomination]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nationalinterest.org/blog/the-buzz/ronald-reagan-vs-gerald-ford-the-1976-gop-convention-battle-15818|title=Ronald Reagan vs. Gerald Ford: The 1976 GOP Convention Battle Royal|first=Lee|last=Edwards|date=April 16, 2016|website=The National Interest}}</ref> in the 1976 primaries and President [[George H.W. Bush]] was challenged in [[1992 Republican Party presidential primaries|1992]].\n\nIn December 2018, the Trump campaign announced that it was merging its field operations with that of the Republican National Committee's.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/12/18/politics/trump-2020-campaign-rnc/index.html|title=Trump gears up for 2020 re-election by tightening grip on party|author=Dan Merica|website=Cnn.com|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}</ref> The following month at the RNC's winter meeting in New Mexico, while acknowledging that declaring the President the party's provisional nominee would break FEC rules, the RNC voted to endorse him informally by voting to give him its \"full support.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2019/jan/26/rnc-vote-unanimous-support-trump-no-endorse-2020/|title=RNC unanimously pledges 'undivided support' for Trump, stops short of explicit 2020 endorsement|first=Andrew|last=Blake|date=January 26, 2019|publisher=The Washington Times|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== United States presidents ===\n\n===U.S. Executive Branch officials===\n====Current====\n[[File:Mike Pence official Vice Presidential portrait (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|[[Mike Pence]]]]\n[[File:Ben_Carson_official_portrait.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Ben Carson]]]]\n[[File:Nikki Haley official photo.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Nikki Haley]]]]\n* [[Mike Pence]], [[Vice